  "prompt": "What three books should an economics undergraduate read?",
  "response": "Here are three highly recommended books for an economics undergraduate that provide foundational knowledge, critical perspectives, and real-world applications:\n\n1. **\"Principles of Economics\" by N. Gregory Mankiw**  \n   - This is a classic introductory textbook that covers the fundamental principles of microeconomics and macroeconomics. It\u2019s written in an accessible style and includes real-world examples, making it a staple for many economics courses.\n\n2. **\"Capital in the Twenty-First Century\" by Thomas Piketty**  \n   - This seminal work explores the dynamics of wealth and income inequality over time. It\u2019s a thought-provoking book that combines historical analysis with economic theory, offering insights into the challenges of modern capitalism.\n\n3. **\"Freakonomics: A Rogue Economist Explores the Hidden Side of Everything\" by Steven D. Levitt and Stephen J. Dubner**  \n   - This popular book applies economic thinking to unconventional topics, demonstrating how economic principles can explain everyday phenomena. It\u2019s engaging and helps students see the relevance of economics in the real world.\n\nThese books provide a mix of theoretical grounding, critical analysis, and practical applications, offering a well-rounded perspective for an economics undergraduate.",
